<glossary>
<definition id="fs-id1170902131900">
<term>diode</term>
<meaning id="fs-id1170903928987">nonohmic circuit device that allows current flow in only one direction</meaning>
</definition>
<definition id="fs-id1170902405808">
<term>Ohm’s law</term>
<meaning id="fs-id1170902381048">empirical relation stating that the current <emphasis effect="italics">I</emphasis> is proportional to the potential difference <emphasis effect="italics">V</emphasis>; it is often written as <m:math><m:mrow><m:mi>V</m:mi><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mi>I</m:mi><m:mi>R</m:mi></m:mrow></m:math>, where <emphasis effect="italics">R</emphasis> is the resistance</meaning>
</definition>
<definition id="fs-id1170902149697">
<term>ohmic</term>
<meaning id="fs-id1170902342874">type of a material for which Ohm’s law is valid, that is, the voltage drop across the device is equal to the current times the resistance</meaning>
</definition>
<definition id="fs-id1170903799858">
<term>nonohmic</term>
<meaning id="fs-id1170904170235">type of a material for which Ohm’s law is not valid</meaning>
</definition>
</glossary>
